 (690,'Split Squat with Dumbbells','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Position yourself into a staggered stance with the rear foot elevated and front foot forward.</li>\r\n<li> Hold a dumbbell in each hand, letting them hang at the sides. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Begin by descending, flexing your knee and hip to lower your body down. Maintain good posture througout the movement. Keep the front knee in line with the foot as you perform the exercise.</li>\r\n<li> At the bottom of the movement, drive through the heel to extend the knee and hip to return to the starting position.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1071,1072,630,2,63,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/split-squat-with-dumbbells',2,'9.7',4,5,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/800/Male/m/800_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/800/Male/m/800_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/800/Female/m/800_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/800/Female/m/800_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (691,'Squat Jerk','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Standing with the weight racked on the front of the shoulders, begin with the dip. With your feet directly under your hips, flex the knees without moving the hips backward. Go down only slightly, and reverse direction as powerfully as possible. Drive through the heels create as much speed and force as possible, and be sure to move your head out of the way as the bar leaves the shoulders.</li>\r\n<li> At this moment as the feet leave the floor, the feet must be placed into the receiving position as quickly as possible. In the brief moment the feet are not actively driving against the platform, the athlete&acirc;&#128;&#153;s effort to push the bar up will drive them down. The feet should move forcefully to just outside the hips, turned out as necessary. Receive the bar with your body in a full squat and the arms fully extended overhead.</li>\r\n<li> Keeping the bar aligned over the front of the heels, your head and chest up, drive throught heels of the feet to move to a standing position. Carefully return the weight to floor.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1073,1074,640,2,63,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/squat-jerk',2,'0.0',4,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/721/Male/m/721_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/721/Male/m/721_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/721/Male/m/721_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/721/Male/m/721_4.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/721/Female/m/721_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/721/Female/m/721_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/721/Female/m/721_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/721/Female/m/721_4.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (692,'Squat with Bands','\n        <p>\n         </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li> Set up the bands on the sleeves, secured to either band pegs, the rack, or dumbbells so that there is appropriate tension. </li>\r\n<li>  Begin by stepping under the bar and placing it across the back of the shoulders. Squeeze your shoulder blades together and rotate your elbows forward, attempting to bend the bar across your shoulders. Remove the bar from the rack, creating a tight arch in your lower back, and step back into position. Place your feet wide for more emphasis on the back, glutes, adductors, and hamstrings. Keep your head facing forward.</li>\r\n<li> With your back, shoulders, and core tight, push your knees and butt out and you begin your descent. Sit back with your hips as much as possible. Ideally, your shins should be perpendicular to the ground. Lower bar position necessitates a greater torso lean to keep the bar over the heels. Continue until you break parallel, which is defined as the crease of the hip being in line with the top of the knee. </li>\r\n<li>Keeping the weight on your heels and pushing your feet and knees out, drive upward as you lead the movement with your head. Continue upward, maintaining tightness head to toe, until you have returned to the starting position.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1075,1076,650,2,63,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/squat-with-bands',2,'0.0',4,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/704/Male/m/704_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/704/Male/m/704_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/704/Female/m/704_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/704/Female/m/704_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (693,'Squat with Chains','\n        <p>\n         </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To set up the chains, begin by looping the leader chain over the sleeves of the bar. The heavy chain should be attached using a snap hook. Adjust the length of the lead chain so that a few links are still on the floor at the top of the movement.</li>\r\n<li>  Begin by stepping under the bar and placing it across the back of the shoulders. Squeeze your shoulder blades together and rotate your elbows forward, attempting to bend the bar across your shoulders. Remove the bar from the rack, creating a tight arch in your lower back, and step back into position. Place your feet wide for more emphasis on the back, glutes, adductors, and hamstrings. Keep your head facing forward.</li>\r\n<li> With your back, shoulders, and core tight, push your knees and butt out and you begin your descent. Sit back with your hips as much as possible. Ideally, your shins should be perpendicular to the ground. Lower bar position necessitates a greater torso lean to keep the bar over the heels. Continue until you break parallel, which is defined as the crease of the hip being in line with the top of the knee. </li>\r\n<li>Keeping the weight on your heels and pushing your feet and knees out, drive upward as you lead the movement with your head. Continue upward, maintaining tightness head to toe, until you have returned to the starting position.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1077,1078,660,2,63,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/squat-with-chains',2,'9.0',4,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/705/Male/m/705_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/705/Male/m/705_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/705/Female/m/705_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/705/Female/m/705_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (694,'Squats - With Bands','\n        <p>\n        </p><p></p><ol><li> To start out, make sure that the exercise band is at an even split between both the left and right side of the body.  To do this, use your hands to grab both sides of the band and place both feet in the middle of the band.  Your feet should be shoulder width apart from each other.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> When holding the bands, they should be the same height on each side.  You should be using a pronated grip (palms facing forward) and have the handles of the bands next to your face for this exercise.  This is the starting position.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Slowly start to bend the knees and lower the legs so that your thighs are parallel to the floor while exhaling.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Use the heel of your feet to push your body up to the starting position as you exhale.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1079,1080,670,2,63,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/squats-with-bands',2,'6.5',1,1,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/260/Male/m/260_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/260/Male/m/260_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/260/Female/m/260_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/260/Female/m/260_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (695,'Trap Bar Deadlift','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>For this exercise load a trap bar, also known as a hex bar, to an appropriate weight resting on the ground. Stand in the center of the apparatus and grasp both handles.</li>\r\n<li> Lower your hips, look forward with your head and keep your chest up.</li>\r\n<li> Begin the movement by driving through the heels and extend your hips and knees. Avoid rounding your back at all times.</li>\r\n<li> At the completion of the movement, lower the weight back to the ground under control.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1081,1082,680,2,63,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/trap-bar-deadlift',2,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/921/Male/m/921_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/921/Male/m/921_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/921/Female/m/921_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/921/Female/m/921_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (696,'Weighted Sissy Squat','\n        <p>\n        </p><p></p><ol><li> Standing upright, with feet at shoulder width and toes raised, use one hand to hold onto the beams of a squat rack and the opposite arm to hold a plate on top of your chest.  This is your starting position.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> As you use one arm to hold yourself, bend at the knees and slowly lower your torso toward the ground by bringing your pelvis and knees forward.  Inhale as you go down and stop when your upper and lower legs almost create a 90-degree angle.  Hold the stretch position for a second.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> After your one second hold, use your thigh muscles to bring your torso back up to the starting position.  Exhale as you move up.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Repeat for the recommended amount of times.</li>\r\n</ol><p><strong>Caution:</strong> This exercise is to be avoided if you suffer from knee problems as it can stress the knee.  Also, make sure that there is nothing behind you; as in the case that you lose your balance and fall, that way nothing will hit you on the head causing an injury.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Variations:</strong> If you are new to this exercise, you can start by using two arms (so you\'ll need the two beams of the squat rack in front of you to hold yourself).   As you become more advanced then just use one arm.  Once that becomes easy, you can use the opposite arm to hold a plate on top of your chest.</p>\n    \n',0,1083,1084,690,2,63,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/weighted-sissy-squat',2,'0.0',1,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/335/Male/m/335_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/335/Male/m/335_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/335/Female/m/335_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/335/Female/m/335_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (697,'Weighted Squat','\n        <p>\n        </p><p></p><ol><li> Start by positioning two flat benches shoulder width apart from each other.  Stand on top of them and wrap the weighted belt around your waist with the amount of weight you feel comfortable with. Make sure your toes are facing out.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Once you are standing straight up with the weight hanging in between your legs, position your arms so that they are fully extended to the side of your body.  This is the starting position.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Begin by bending the knees as you maintain a straight posture with the head up.  Continue down until the angle between the upper leg and the calves becomes slightly less than 90-degrees (which is the point in which the upper legs are below parallel to the floor).  Inhale as you perform this portion of the movement. <strong>Tip:</strong> If you performed the exercise correctly, the front of the knees should make an imaginary straight line with the toes that are perpendicular to the front.  If your knees are past that imaginary line (if they are past your toes) then you are placing undue stress on the knee and the exercise has been performed incorrectly.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Begin to move the body back up by pushing the floor of the flat bench with the ball of your foot mainly as you straighten the legs again and go back to the starting position.  Exhale as you perform this portion of the exercise.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.</li>\r\n</ol><p><strong>Variations:</strong> Instead of using flat benches, you can use any other sort of raised platforms as long as they are sturdy and safe to use.</p>\n    \n',0,1085,1086,700,2,63,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/weighted-squat',2,'7.5',1,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/336/Male/m/336_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/336/Male/m/336_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/336/Female/m/336_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/336/Female/m/336_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (698,'Wide Stance Barbell Squat','\n        <p>\n        </p><p></p><ol><li> This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes.  To begin, first set the bar on a rack that best matches your height.  Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, step under the bar and place the back of your shoulders (slightly below the neck) across it.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Hold on to the bar using both arms at each side and lift it off the rack by first pushing with your legs and at the same time straightening your torso.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Step away from the rack and position your legs using a wider-than-shoulder-width stance with the toes slightly pointed out.  Keep your head up at all times as looking down will get you off balance, and also maintain a straight back.  This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n	<li> Begin to slowly lower the bar by bending the knees as you maintain a straight posture with the head up.  Continue down until the angle between the upper leg and the calves becomes slightly less than 90-degrees (which is the point in which the upper legs are below parallel to the floor).  Inhale as you perform this portion of the movement.  <strong>Tip:</strong> If you performed the exercise correctly, the front of the knees should make an imaginary straight line with the toes that is perpendicular to the front.  If your knees are past that imaginary line (if they are past your toes) then you are placing undue stress on the knee and the exercise has been performed incorrectly.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Begin to raise the bar as you exhale by pushing the floor with the heel of your foot as you straighten the legs again and go back to the starting position.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.</li>\r\n</ol><p><strong>Caution:</strong>  This is not an exercise to be taken lightly.  If you have back issues, substitute it with the dumbbell squat variation or a leg press instead.  If you have a healthy back, ensure perfect form and never slouch the back forward as this can cause back injury. Be cautious as well with the weight used; in case of doubt, use less weight rather than more.  The squat is a very safe exercise but only if performed properly.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p><strong>Variations:</strong></p> \r\n\r\n<ul><p>As previously mentioned, there are various stances that can be used depending on what you want to emphasize.</p>  \r\n\r\n<p>You can also place a small block under the heels if you lack ankle flexibility.</p>  \r\n\r\n<p>Dumbbells can be used as well for resistance by holding them to your sides.  The use of wrist wraps is a necessity due to the amount of weights used.  I find this an excellent variation when my lower back begins to act up after many weeks of regular barbell squats.  (<strong>Note:</strong> For wide stance dumbbell squats you will have to hold the dumbbells in between your legs as opposed to both sides in order to be able to distance your legs sufficiently).</p>  \r\n\r\n<p>Another way to perform these is by using a weight belt and attaching weights to it in between the legs.  This variation is referred to as weight belt squats which need to be performed with the legs placed on two well secured, raised but separated platforms that allow the weights to go up and down in the middle. This exercise is an excellent choice for people with lower back problems. p&gt; \r\n</p></ul>\n',0,1087,1088,710,2,63,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/wide-stance-barbell-squat',2,'8.0',1,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/44/Male/m/44_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/44/Male/m/44_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/44/Female/m/44_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/44/Female/m/44_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (699,'Zercher Squats','\n        <p>\n        </p><p></p><ol><li> This exercise is best performed inside a squat rack for safety purposes.  To begin, first set the bar on a rack that best matches your height.  The correct height should be anywhere above the waist but below the chest. Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, lock your hands together and place the bar on top of your arms in between the forearm and upper arm.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Lift the bar up so that it is resting on top of your forearms.  If you are holding the bar properly, it should look as if you have your arms crossed but with a bar running across them.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Step away from the rack and position your legs using a shoulder width medium stance with the toes slightly pointed out.  Keep your head up at all times as looking down will get you off balance and also maintain a straight back.  This will be your starting position.  (<strong>Note</strong>: For the purposes of this discussion we will use the medium stance described above which targets overall development; however you can choose any of the three stances discussed in the foot stances section).</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Begin to lower the bar by bending the knees as you maintain a straight posture with the head up.  Continue down until the angle between the upper leg and the calves becomes slightly less than 90-degrees (which is the point in which the upper legs are below parallel to the floor).  Inhale as you perform this portion of the movement.  <strong>Tip:</strong> If you performed the exercise correctly, the front of the knees should make an imaginary straight line with the toes that is perpendicular to the front.  If your knees are past that imaginary line (if they are past your toes) then you are placing undue stress on the knee and the exercise has been performed incorrectly.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Begin to raise the bar as you exhale by pushing the floor with the ball of your foot mainly as you straighten the legs again and go back to the starting position.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.</li>\r\n</ol><p><strong>Caution:</strong> This exercise is not to be taken lightly as you are applying a lot of pressure to your arms when lifting the barbell.  It is always a good idea to have a spotter as they can help you keep proper form.  Also, make sure that your back is kept straight as bending it can cause an injury.</p>\n    \n',0,1089,1090,720,2,63,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/zercher-squats',2,'6.9',1,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/284/Male/m/284_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/284/Male/m/284_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/284/Female/m/284_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/284/Female/m/284_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (700,'All Fours Quad Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li> Start off on your hands and knees, then lift your leg off the floor and hold the foot with your  hand. </li>\r\n<li> Use your hand to hold the foot or ankle, keeping the knee fully flexed, stretching the quadriceps and hip flexors. </li>\r\n<li> Focus on extending your hips, thrusting them towards the floor. Hold for 10-20 seconds and then switch sides.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1361,1362,10,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/all-fours-quad-stretch',3,'5.3',4,3,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/581/Male/m/581_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/581/Male/m/581_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/581/Female/m/581_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/581/Female/m/581_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (701,'Frog Hops','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Stand with your hands behind your head, and squat down keeping your torso upright and your head up. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Jump forward several feet, avoiding jumping unnecessarily high. As your feet contact the ground, absorb the impact through your legs, and jump again. Repeat this action 5-10 times.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1363,1364,20,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/frog-hops',2,'2.5',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/588/Male/m/588_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/588/Male/m/588_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/588/Female/m/588_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/588/Female/m/588_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/588/Female/m/588_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (702,'Intermediate Hip Flexor and Quad Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Lie face down on the floor, with a rope, belt, or band looped around one foot.</li>\r\n<li> Flex the knee and extend the hip of the leg to be stretched, using both hands to pull on the belt. Your knee and your hip should come off of the floor, creating tension in the hip flexors and quadriceps. Hold the stretch for 10-20 seconds, and repeat on the other leg.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1365,1366,30,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/intermediate-hip-flexor-and-quad-stretch',2,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/596/Male/m/596_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/596/Male/m/596_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/596/Female/m/596_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/596/Female/m/596_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (703,'Iron Crosses (stretch)','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Lie face down on the floor, with your arms extended out to your side, palms pressed to the floor. This will be your starting position. </li>\r\n<li>To begin, flex one knee and bring that leg across the back of your body, attempting to touch it to the ground near the opposite hand.</li>\r\n<li> Promptly return the leg to the starting postion, and quickly repeat with the other leg. Continue alternating for 10-20 repetitions.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1367,1368,40,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/iron-crosses-stretch',2,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/597/Male/m/597_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/597/Male/m/597_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/597/Female/m/597_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/597/Female/m/597_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (704,'Kneeling Hip Flexor','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Kneel on a mat and bring your right knee up so the bottom of your foot is on the floor and extend your left leg out behind you so the top of your foot is on the floor.</li>\r\n<li> Shift your weight forward until you feel a stretch in your hip. Hold for 15 seconds, then repeat for your other side.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1369,1370,50,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/kneeling-hip-flexor',1,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/476/Male/m/476_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/476/Male/m/476_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/476/Female/m/476_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/476/Female/m/476_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (705,'Looking At Ceiling','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Kneel on the floor, holding your heels with both hands.</li>\r\n<li> Lift your buttocks up and forward while bringing your head back to look up at the ceiling, to give an arch in your back.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1371,1372,60,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/looking-at-ceiling',1,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/455/Male/m/455_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/455/Male/m/455_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/455/Female/m/455_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/455/Female/m/455_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (706,'On Your Side Quad Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Start off by lying on your right side, with your right knee bent at a 90-degree angle resting on the floor in front of you (this stabilizes the torso).</li>\r\n<li> Bend your left knee behind you and hold your left foot with your left hand. To stretch your hip flexor, press your left hip forward as you push your left foot back into your hand. Switch sides.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1373,1374,70,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/on-your-side-quad-stretch',1,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/402/Male/m/402_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/402/Male/m/402_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/402/Female/m/402_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/402/Female/m/402_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (707,'On-Your-Back Quad Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Lie on a flat bench or step, and hang one leg and arm over the side.</li>\r\n<li> Bend the knee and hold the top of the foot. As you do this, be careful not to arch your lower back.</li>\r\n<li> Pull the belly button to the spine to stay in neutral. Press your foot down and into your hand. To add the hip stretch, lift the hip of the leg you\'re holding up toward the ceiling.</li>\r\n<li> Switch sides.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1375,1376,80,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/on-your-back-quad-stretch',1,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/430/Male/m/430_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/430/Male/m/430_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/430/Female/m/430_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/430/Female/m/430_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (708,'One Half Locust','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li> Lie facedown on the floor. </li>\r\n<li>Put your left hand under your left hipbone to pad your hip and pubic bone.</li>\r\n<li> Bend your right knee so you can hold the foot in your right hand.</li>\r\n<li> Lift the foot in the air and simultaneously lift your shoulders off the floor. This also stretches the right hip flexor and the chest and shoulders. Switch sides. If it doesn\'t bother your back, you can try it with both arms and legs at the same time.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1377,1378,90,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/one-half-locust',3,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/400/Male/m/400_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/400/Male/m/400_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/400/Female/m/400_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/400/Female/m/400_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (709,'Quad Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Lay on your side. Loop a belt, rope, or band around your top foot. Flex the knee and extend your hip, attempting to touch your glutes with your foot, and holding the belt with your hands. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> With the belt being held over the shoulder or overhead, gently pull to increase the stretch in the quadriceps. Hold for 10-20 seconds, and then switch sides.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1379,1380,100,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/quad-stretch',3,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/614/Male/m/614_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/614/Male/m/614_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/614/Female/m/614_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/614/Female/m/614_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (710,'Quadriceps-SMR','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Lay facedown on the floor with your weight supported by your hands or forearms. Place a foam roll underneath one leg on the quadriceps, and keep the foot off of the ground. Make sure to relax the leg as much as possible. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Shifting as much weight onto the leg to be stretched as is tolerable, roll over the foam from above the knee to below the hip, holding points of tension for 10-30 seconds. Switch sides.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1381,1382,110,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/quadriceps-smr',1,'0.0',4,8,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/615/Male/m/615_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/615/Male/m/615_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/615/Female/m/615_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/615/Female/m/615_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (711,'Rear Leg Raises','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Place yourself on your hands knees on an exercise mat. Your head should be looking forward and the bend of the knees should create a 90-degree angle between the hamstrings and the calves. This will be your starting position. </li>\r\n<li> Extend one leg up and behind you. The knee and hip should both extend. Repeat for 5-10 repetitions, and then switch sides.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1383,1384,120,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/rear-leg-raises',3,'0.0',4,3,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/634/Male/m/634_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/634/Male/m/634_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/634/Female/m/634_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/634/Female/m/634_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (712,'Sit Squats','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Stand with your feet shoulder width apart. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li>  Begin the movement by flexing your knees and hips, sitting back with your hips.</li>\r\n<li> Continue until you have squatted a portion of the way down, but are above parallel, and quickly reverse the motion until you return to the starting position. Repeat for 5-10 repetitions.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1385,1386,130,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/sit-squats',3,'7.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/637/Male/m/637_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/637/Male/m/637_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/637/Female/m/637_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/637/Female/m/637_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/637/Female/m/637_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (713,'Standing Elevated Quad Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Start by standing with your back about two to three feet away from a bench or step.</li>\r\n<li> Lift one leg behind you and rest your foot on the step,either on your instep or the ball of your foot, whichever you find most comfortable. </li>\r\n<li>Keep your supporting knee slightly bent and avoid letting that knee extend out beyond your toes. Switch sides.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1387,1388,140,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/standing-elevated-quad-stretch',3,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/443/Male/m/443_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/443/Male/m/443_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/443/Female/m/443_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/443/Female/m/443_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (714,'Standing Hip Flexors','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Stand up straight with the spine vertical, the left foot slightly in front of the right. </li>\r\n<li>Bend both knees and lift the back heel off the floor as you press the right hip forward. You can\'t get a thorough, deep stretch in this position, however, because it\'s hard to relax the hip flexor and stand on it at the same time. Switch sides.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1389,1390,150,2,626,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/standing-hip-flexors',1,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/444/Male/m/444_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/444/Male/m/444_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/444/Female/m/444_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/444/Female/m/444_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (715,'Alternate Leg Diagonal Bound','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Assume a comfortable stance with one foot slightly in front of the other.</li>\r\n<li> Begin by pushing off with the front leg, driving the opposite knee forward and as high as possible before landing. Attempt to cover as much distance to each side with each bound. </li>\r\n<li>  It may help to use a line on the ground to guage distance from side to side.</li>\r\n<li> Repeat the sequence with the other leg.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1553,1554,10,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/alternate-leg-diagonal-bound',2,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/760/Male/m/760_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/760/Male/m/760_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/760/Male/m/760_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/760/Male/m/760_4.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/760/Female/m/760_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/760/Female/m/760_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/760/Female/m/760_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/760/Female/m/760_4.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (716,'Depth Jump Leap','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>For this drill you will need two boxes or benches, one 12 to 16 inches high and the other 22 to 26 inches high.</li>\r\n<li> Stand on one of the two boxes with arms at the sides; feet should be together and slightly off the edge as in the depth jump. Place the other box approximately two or three feet in front of and facing the performer.</li>\r\n<li> Begin by dropping off the initial box, landing and simultaneously taking off with both feet.</li>\r\n<li> Rebound by driving upward and outward as intensely as possible, using the arms and full extension of the body to jump onto the higher box. Again, allow the legs to absorb the impact. \r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1555,1556,20,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/depth-jump-leap',2,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/775/Male/m/775_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/775/Male/m/775_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/775/Male/m/775_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/775/Male/m/775_4.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/775/Female/m/775_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/775/Female/m/775_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/775/Female/m/775_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (717,'Double Leg Butt Kick','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Begin standing with your knees slightly bent.</li>\r\n<li> Quickly squat a short distance, flexing the hips and knees, and immediately extend to jump for maximum vertical height.</li>\r\n<li> As you go up, tuck your heels by flexing the knees, attempting to touch the buttocks.</li>\r\n<li> Finish the motion by landing with the knees only partially bent, using your legs to absorb the impact.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1557,1558,30,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/double-leg-butt-kick',2,'0.0',4,3,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/778/Male/m/778_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/778/Male/m/778_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/778/Male/m/778_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/778/Female/m/778_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/778/Female/m/778_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (718,'Fast Skipping','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Start in a relaxed position with one leg slightly forward. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Skip by executing a step-hop pattern of right-right-step to left-left-step, and so on, alternating back and forth.</li>\r\n<li> Perform fast skips by maintaining close contact with the ground and reduce air time, moving as quickly as possible. \r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1559,1560,40,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/fast-skipping',2,'0.0',4,3,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/780/Male/m/780_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/780/Male/m/780_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/780/Male/m/780_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/780/Male/m/780_4.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/780/Female/m/780_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/780/Female/m/780_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/780/Female/m/780_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/780/Female/m/780_4.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (719,'Front Cone Hops (or hurdle hops)','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Set up a row of cones or other small barriers, placing them a few feet apart.</li>\r\n<li> Stand in front of the first cone with your feet shoulder width apart. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Begin by jumping with both feet over the first cone, swinging both arms as you jump. </li>\r\n<li>Absorb the impact of landing by bending the knees, rebounding out of the first leap by jumping over the next cone.</li>\r\n<li> Continue until you have jumped over all of the cones.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1561,1562,50,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/front-cone-hops-or-hurdle-hops',2,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/783/Male/m/783_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/783/Male/m/783_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/783/Male/m/783_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/783/Male/m/783_4.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/783/Female/m/783_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/783/Female/m/783_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/783/Female/m/783_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (720,'Mountain Climbers','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Begin in a pushup position, with your weight supported by your hands and toes. Flexing the knee and hip, bring one leg until the knee is approximately under the hip. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Explosively reverse the positions of your legs, extending the bent leg until the leg is straight and supported by the toe, and bringing the other foot up with the hip and knee flexed. Repeat in an alternating fashion for 20-30 seconds.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1563,1564,60,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/mountain-climbers',2,'8.3',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/608/Male/m/608_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/608/Male/m/608_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/608/Female/m/608_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/608/Female/m/608_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/608/Female/m/608_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (721,'Quick Leap','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>You will need a box for this exerise.</li>\r\n<li> Begin facing the box standing 1-2 feet from its edge.</li>\r\n<li> By utilizing your hips, hop onto the box, landing on both legs. Ensure that you land with your legs bent and your feet flat.</li>\r\n<li> Immediately upon landing, fully extend through the entire body and swing your arms overhead to explode off of the box. Use your legs to absorb the impact of landing. \r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1565,1566,70,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/quick-leap',2,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/810/Male/m/810_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/810/Male/m/810_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/810/Male/m/810_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/810/Female/m/810_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/810/Female/m/810_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/810/Female/m/810_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (722,'Rocket Jump','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Begin in a relaxed stance with your feet shoulder width apart and hold your arms close to the body.</li>\r\n<li> To initiate the move, squat down halfway and explode back up as high as possible.</li>\r\n<li> Fully extend your entire body, reaching overhead as far as possible. As you land,  absorb your impact through the legs.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1567,1568,80,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/rocket-jump',2,'0.0',4,3,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/812/Male/m/812_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/812/Male/m/812_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/812/Female/m/812_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/812/Female/m/812_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (723,'Scissors Jump','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li> Assume a lunge stance position with one foot forward with the knee bent, and the rear knee nearly touching the ground.</li>\r\n<li> Ensure that the front knee is over the midline of the foot. Extending through both legs, jump as high as possible, swinging your arms to gain lift.</li>\r\n<li> As you jump as high as you can, switch the position of your legs, moving your front leg to the back and the rear leg to the front.</li>\r\n<li> As you land, absorb the impact through the legs by adopting the lunge position, and repeat.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1569,1570,90,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/scissors-jump',2,'0.0',4,3,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/813/Male/m/813_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/813/Male/m/813_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/813/Male/m/813_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/813/Male/m/813_4.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/813/Female/m/813_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/813/Female/m/813_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/813/Female/m/813_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/813/Female/m/813_4.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (724,'Side Hop-Sprint','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Stand to the side of a cone or hurdle.</li>\r\n<li> Begin this drill by hopping sideways over the obstacle, rebounding out of your landing to hop back to where you started.</li>\r\n<li> Hop for a prescribed number or repetitions as quickly as possible, and finish this drill by sprinting a short distance upon landing the last hop.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1571,1572,100,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/side-hop-sprint',2,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/816/Male/m/816_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/816/Male/m/816_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/816/Male/m/816_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/816/Male/m/816_4.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/816/Female/m/816_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/816/Female/m/816_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/816/Female/m/816_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/816/Female/m/816_4.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (725,'Side to Side Box Shuffle','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Stand to one side of the box with your left foot resting on the middle of it.</li>\r\n<li> To begin, jump up and over to the other side of the box, landing with your right foot on top of the box and your left foot on the floor. Swing your arms to aid your movement.</li>\r\n<li> Continue shuffling back and forth across the box.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1573,1574,110,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/side-to-side-box-shuffle',2,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/817/Male/m/817_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/817/Male/m/817_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/817/Male/m/817_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/817/Male/m/817_4.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/817/Female/m/817_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/817/Female/m/817_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/817/Female/m/817_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/817/Female/m/817_4.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (726,'Single Leg Butt Kick','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Begin by standing on one leg, with the bent knee raised. This will be your start position. </li>\r\n<li>Using a countermovement jump, take off upward by extending the hip, knee, and ankle of the grounded leg.</li>\r\n<li> Immediately flex the knee and attempt to touch your butt with the heel of your jumping leg.</li>\r\n<li> Return the leg to a partially bent position underneath the hips and land. Your opposite leg should stay in relatively the same position throughout the drill.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1575,1576,120,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/single-leg-butt-kick',2,'0.0',4,3,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/819/Male/m/819_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/819/Male/m/819_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/819/Male/m/819_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/819/Female/m/819_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/819/Female/m/819_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/819/Female/m/819_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/819/Female/m/819_4.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (727,'Single Leg Push-off','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Stand on the ground with one foot resting on the box, heel close to the edge.</li>\r\n<li> Push off with your foot on top of the box, trying to gain as much height as possible by extending through the hip and knee.</li>\r\n<li> Land with the same foot on top of the box, returning your other foot back to the start position.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1577,1578,130,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/single-leg-push-off',2,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/818/Male/m/818_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/818/Male/m/818_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/818/Female/m/818_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/818/Female/m/818_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (728,'Single-Leg Stride Jump','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Stand to the side of a box with your inside foot on top of it, close to the edge.</li>\r\n<li> Begin by swinging the arms upward as you push through the top leg, jumping upward as high as possible. Attempt to drive the opposite knee upward.</li>\r\n<li> Land in the same position that you started, using your inside leg to decelerate the impact.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1579,1580,140,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/single-leg-stride-jump',2,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/824/Male/m/824_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/824/Male/m/824_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/824/Male/m/824_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/824/Male/m/824_4.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/824/Female/m/824_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/824/Female/m/824_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/824/Female/m/824_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/824/Female/m/824_4.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (729,'Split Jump','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Assume a lunge stance position with one foot forward with the knee bent, and the rear knee nearly touching the ground.</li>\r\n<li> Ensure that the front knee is over the midline of the foot.</li>\r\n<li> Extending through both legs, jump as high as possible, swinging your arms to gain lift.</li>\r\n<li> As you jump, bring your feet together, and move them back to their initial positions as you land.</li>\r\n<li> Absorb the impact by reverting back to the starting position.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1581,1582,150,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/split-jump',2,'0.0',4,3,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/826/Male/m/826_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/826/Male/m/826_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/826/Male/m/826_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/826/Male/m/826_4.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/826/Female/m/826_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/826/Female/m/826_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/826/Female/m/826_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/826/Female/m/826_4.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (730,'Standing Long Jump','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>This drill is best done in sand or other soft landing surface. Ensure that you are able to measure distance. Stand in a partial squat stance with feet shoulder width apart.</li>\r\n<li> Utilizing a big arm swing and a countermovement of the legs, jump forward as far as you can.</li>\r\n<li> Attempt to land with your feet out in front you, reaching as far as possible with your legs.</li>\r\n<li> Measure the distance from your landing point to the starting point and track results.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1583,1584,160,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/standing-long-jump',2,'0.0',4,3,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/831/Male/m/831_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/831/Male/m/831_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/831/Male/m/831_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/831/Male/m/831_4.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/831/Female/m/831_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/831/Female/m/831_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/831/Female/m/831_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/831/Female/m/831_4.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (731,'Star Jump','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n\r\n</p><ol><li>Begin in a relaxed stance with your feet shoulder width apart and hold your arms close to the body. </li>\r\n<li>To initiate the move, squat down halfway and explode back up as high as possible. Fully extend your entire body, spreading your legs and arms away from the body.</li>\r\n<li> As you land, bring your limbs back in and absorb your impact through the legs.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1585,1586,170,2,627,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/star-jump',2,'0.0',4,3,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/835/Male/m/835_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/835/Male/m/835_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/835/Female/m/835_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/835/Female/m/835_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (733,'Bicycling','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, seat yourself on the bike and adjust the seat to your height.</li>  Wear protective gear to avoid possible injury. Ensure that you are courteous to vehicles and pedestrians, and that you obey the rules of the road.\r\n</ol>\r\nCycling offers convenience, cardiovascular benefits, and has less impact than other activities. A 150 lb person will burn about 280 calories cycling at a moderate rate for 30 minutes, compared to 450 calories or more running. \r\n\n    \n',6,2,3,10,1,47,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/bicycling',3,'9.4',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/646/Male/m/646_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/646/Male/m/646_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/646/Male/m/646_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/646/Female/m/646_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/646/Female/m/646_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/646/Female/m/646_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (736,'Jogging-Treadmill','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, step onto the treadmill and select the desired option from the menu. Most treadmills have a manual setting, or you can select a program to run. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. Elevation can be adjusted to change the intensity of the workout. </li>\r\n<li>\r\nTreadmills offer convenience, cardiovascular benefits, and usually have less impact than jogging outside. A 150 lb person will burn almost 250 calories jogging for 30 minutes, compared to more than 450 calories running. Maintain proper posture as you jog, and only hold onto the handles when necessary, such as when dismounting or checking your heart rate. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,8,9,40,1,47,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/jogging-treadmill',3,'8.4',4,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/649/Male/m/649_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/649/Male/m/649_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/649/Female/m/649_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/649/Female/m/649_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (737,'Recumbent Bike','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, seat yourself on the bike and adjust the seat to your height. </li>\r\n<li> Select the desired option from the menu. You may have to start pedaling to turn it on. You can use the manual setting, or you can select a program to use. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. The level of resistance can be changed throughout the workout. The handles can be used to monitor your heart rate to help you stay at an appropriate intensity.</li>\r\n<li>\r\nRecumbent bikes offer convenience, cardiovascular benefits, and have less impact than other activities. A 150 lb person will burn about 230 calories cycling at a moderate rate for 30 minutes, compared to 450 calories or more running. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,10,11,50,1,47,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/recumbent-bike',3,'9.0',4,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/650/Male/m/650_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/650/Male/m/650_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/650/Female/m/650_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/650/Female/m/650_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (738,'Rope Jumping','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Hold an end of the rope in each hand. Position the rope behind you on the ground. Raise your arms up and turn the rope over your head bringing it down in front of you. When it reaches the ground, jump over it. Find a good turning pace that can be maintained. Different speeds and techniques can be used to introduce variation. </li>\r\n<li>Rope jumping is exciting, challenges your coordination, and requires a lot of energy. A 150 lb person will burn about 350 calories jumping rope for 30 minutes, compared to over 450 calories running. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,12,13,60,1,47,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/rope-jumping',3,'9.7',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/651/Male/m/651_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/651/Male/m/651_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/651/Female/m/651_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/651/Female/m/651_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (739,'Rowing, Stationary','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, seat yourself on the rower. Make sure that your heels are resting comfortably against the base of the foot pedals and that the straps are secured. Select the program that you wish to use, if applicable. Sit up straight and bend forward at the hips. </li>\r\n<li>\r\nThere are three phases of movement when using a rower. The first phase is when you come forward on the rower. Your knees are bent and against your chest. Your upper body is leaning slightly forward while still maintaining good posture.\r\nNext, push against the foot pedals and extend your legs while bringing your hands to your upper abdominal area, squeezing your shoulders back as you do so. To avoid straining your back, use primarily your leg and hip muscles. </li>\r\n<li>\r\nThe recovery phase simply involves straightening your arms, bending the knees, and bringing your body forward again as you transition back into the first phase. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,14,15,70,1,47,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/rowing-stationary',3,'8.4',4,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/652/Male/m/652_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/652/Male/m/652_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/652/Male/m/652_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/652/Female/m/652_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/652/Female/m/652_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/652/Female/m/652_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (741,'Skating','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Roller skating is a fun activity which can be effective in improving cardiorespiratory fitness and muscular endurance. It requires relatively good balance and coordination. It is necessary to learn the basics of skating including turning and stopping and to wear protective gear to avoid possible injury. </li>\r\n<li>\r\nYou can skate at a comfortable pace for 30 minutes straight. If you want a cardio challenge, do interval skating &acirc;&#128;&#147; speed skate two minutes of every five minutes, using the remaining three minutes to recover. A 150 lb person will typically burn about 175 calories in 30 minutes skating at a comfortable pace, similar to brisk walking. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,18,19,90,1,47,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/skating',3,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/654/Male/m/654_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/654/Male/m/654_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/654/Male/m/654_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/654/Female/m/654_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/654/Female/m/654_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/654/Female/m/654_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif');
INSERT INTO `exercise_type` (`type_id`,`name`,`description`,`form_type`,`tree_left`,`tree_right`,`tree_order`,`tree_level`,`tree_parent_id`,`link`,`mechanics_type`,`rating`,`force_type`,`equipment`,`type_img`,`guide_img`) VALUES 
 (742,'Stairmaster','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, step onto the stairmaster and select the desired option from the menu. You can choose a manual setting, or you can select a program to run. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. </li>\r\n<li>Pump your legs up and down in an established rhythm, driving the pedals down but not all the way to the floor. It is recommended that you maintain your grip on the handles so that you don&acirc;&#128;&#153;t fall. The handles can be used to monitor your heart rate to help you stay at an appropriate intensity.</li>\r\n<li>\r\nStairmasters offer convenience, cardiovascular benefits, and usually have less impact than running outside. They are typically much harder than other cardio equipment. A 150 lb person will typically burn over 300 calories in 30 minutes, compared to about 175 calories walking. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',4,20,21,100,1,47,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/stairmaster',3,'8.2',4,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/655/Male/m/655_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/655/Male/m/655_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/655/Female/m/655_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/655/Female/m/655_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (743,'Step Mill','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, step onto the stepmill and select the desired option from the menu. You can choose a manual setting, or you can select a program to run. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. Use caution so that you don&acirc;&#128;&#153;t trip as you climb the stairs. It is recommended that you maintain your grip on the handles so that you don&acirc;&#128;&#153;t fall. </li>\r\n<li>\r\n\r\nStepmills offer convenience, cardiovascular benefits, and usually have less impact than running outside while offering a similar rate of calories burned. They are typically much harder than other cardio equipment. A 150 lb person will typically burn over 300 calories in 30 minutes, compared to about 175 calories walking. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,22,23,110,1,47,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/step-mill',3,'0.0',4,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/656/Male/m/656_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/656/Male/m/656_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/656/Female/m/656_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/656/Female/m/656_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/656/Female/m/656_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (744,'Trail Running/Walking','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Running or hiking on trails will get the blood pumping and heart beating almost immediately. Make sure you have good shoes. While you use the muscles in your calves and buttocks to pull yourself up a hill, the knees, joints and ankles absorb the bulk of the pounding coming back down. Take smaller steps as you walk downhill, keep your knees bent to reduce the impact and slow down to avoid falling.</li>\r\n<li> A 150 lb person can burn over 200 calories for 30 minutes walking uphill, compared to 175 on a flat surface. If running the trail, a 150 lb person can burn well over 500 calories in 30 minutes.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,24,25,120,1,47,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/trail-runningwalking',3,'9.2',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/657/Male/m/657_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/657/Male/m/657_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/657/Male/m/657_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/657/Female/m/657_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/657/Female/m/657_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (745,'Walking, Treadmill','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, step onto the treadmill and select the desired option from the menu. Most treadmills have a manual setting, or you can select a program to run. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. Elevation can be adjusted to change the intensity of the workout. </li>\r\n<li>\r\nTreadmills offer convenience, cardiovascular benefits, and usually have less impact than walking outside. When walking, you should move at a moderate to fast pace, not a leisurely one. Being an activity of lower intensity, walking doesn&acirc;&#128;&#153;t burn as many calories as some other activities, but still provides great benefit. A 150 lb person will burn about 175 calories walking 4 miles per hour for 30 minutes, compared to 450 calories running twice as fast. Maintain proper posture as you walk, and only hold onto the handles when necessary, such as when dismounting or checking your heart rate. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,26,27,130,1,47,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/walking-treadmill',3,'5.7',4,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/658/Male/m/658_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/658/Male/m/658_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/658/Female/m/658_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/658/Female/m/658_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (746,'Bicycling','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, seat yourself on the bike and adjust the seat to your height.</li>  Wear protective gear to avoid possible injury. Ensure that you are courteous to vehicles and pedestrians, and that you obey the rules of the road.\r\n</ol>\r\nCycling offers convenience, cardiovascular benefits, and has less impact than other activities. A 150 lb person will burn about 280 calories cycling at a moderate rate for 30 minutes, compared to 450 calories or more running. \r\n\n    \n',1,30,31,10,1,46,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/bicycling',3,'9.4',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/646/Male/m/646_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/646/Male/m/646_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/646/Male/m/646_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/646/Female/m/646_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/646/Female/m/646_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/646/Female/m/646_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (747,'Bicycling, Stationary','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, seat yourself on the bike and adjust the seat to your height.</li>  \r\n<li>Select the desired option from the menu. You may have to start pedaling to turn it on. You can use the manual setting, or you can select a program to use. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. The level of resistance can be changed throughout the workout. The handles can be used to monitor your heart rate to help you stay at an appropriate intensity.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nStationary bikes offer convenience, cardiovascular benefits, and have less impact than other activities. A 150 lb person will burn about 230 calories cycling at a moderate rate for 30 minutes, compared to 450 calories or more running. \r\n\n    \n',6,32,33,20,1,46,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/bicycling-stationary',3,'8.6',4,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/647/Male/m/647_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/647/Male/m/647_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/647/Female/m/647_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/647/Female/m/647_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (748,'Elliptical Trainer','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, step onto the elliptical and select the desired option from the menu. Most ellipticals have a manual setting, or you can select a program to run. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. Elevation can be adjusted to change the intensity of the workout.</li>\r\n<li> The handles can be used to monitor your heart rate to help you stay at an appropriate intensity.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nEllipticals offer convenience, cardiovascular benefits, and have far less impact on joints than ground-based cardio such as running. A 150 lb person will burn on average 387 calories in 30 minutes, compared to more than 450-700 calories running. It&acirc;&#128;&#153;s recommended that you use the arms on the elliptical to create more movement, if your elliptical has them. \r\n\n    \n',4,34,35,30,1,46,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/elliptical-trainer',3,'8.9',4,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/648/Male/m/648_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/648/Male/m/648_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/648/Female/m/648_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/648/Female/m/648_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (749,'Jogging-Treadmill','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, step onto the treadmill and select the desired option from the menu. Most treadmills have a manual setting, or you can select a program to run. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. Elevation can be adjusted to change the intensity of the workout. </li>\r\n<li>\r\nTreadmills offer convenience, cardiovascular benefits, and usually have less impact than jogging outside. A 150 lb person will burn almost 250 calories jogging for 30 minutes, compared to more than 450 calories running. Maintain proper posture as you jog, and only hold onto the handles when necessary, such as when dismounting or checking your heart rate. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,36,37,40,1,46,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/jogging-treadmill',3,'8.4',4,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/649/Male/m/649_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/649/Male/m/649_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/649/Female/m/649_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/649/Female/m/649_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (750,'Recumbent Bike','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, seat yourself on the bike and adjust the seat to your height. </li>\r\n<li> Select the desired option from the menu. You may have to start pedaling to turn it on. You can use the manual setting, or you can select a program to use. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. The level of resistance can be changed throughout the workout. The handles can be used to monitor your heart rate to help you stay at an appropriate intensity.</li>\r\n<li>\r\nRecumbent bikes offer convenience, cardiovascular benefits, and have less impact than other activities. A 150 lb person will burn about 230 calories cycling at a moderate rate for 30 minutes, compared to 450 calories or more running. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,38,39,50,1,46,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/recumbent-bike',3,'9.0',4,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/650/Male/m/650_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/650/Male/m/650_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/650/Female/m/650_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/650/Female/m/650_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (751,'Rope Jumping','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Hold an end of the rope in each hand. Position the rope behind you on the ground. Raise your arms up and turn the rope over your head bringing it down in front of you. When it reaches the ground, jump over it. Find a good turning pace that can be maintained. Different speeds and techniques can be used to introduce variation. </li>\r\n<li>Rope jumping is exciting, challenges your coordination, and requires a lot of energy. A 150 lb person will burn about 350 calories jumping rope for 30 minutes, compared to over 450 calories running. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,40,41,60,1,46,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/rope-jumping',3,'9.7',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/651/Male/m/651_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/651/Male/m/651_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/651/Female/m/651_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/651/Female/m/651_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (752,'Rowing, Stationary','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, seat yourself on the rower. Make sure that your heels are resting comfortably against the base of the foot pedals and that the straps are secured. Select the program that you wish to use, if applicable. Sit up straight and bend forward at the hips. </li>\r\n<li>\r\nThere are three phases of movement when using a rower. The first phase is when you come forward on the rower. Your knees are bent and against your chest. Your upper body is leaning slightly forward while still maintaining good posture.\r\nNext, push against the foot pedals and extend your legs while bringing your hands to your upper abdominal area, squeezing your shoulders back as you do so. To avoid straining your back, use primarily your leg and hip muscles. </li>\r\n<li>\r\nThe recovery phase simply involves straightening your arms, bending the knees, and bringing your body forward again as you transition back into the first phase. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,42,43,70,1,46,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/rowing-stationary',3,'8.4',4,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/652/Male/m/652_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/652/Male/m/652_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/652/Male/m/652_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/652/Female/m/652_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/652/Female/m/652_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/652/Female/m/652_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (754,'Skating','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Roller skating is a fun activity which can be effective in improving cardiorespiratory fitness and muscular endurance. It requires relatively good balance and coordination. It is necessary to learn the basics of skating including turning and stopping and to wear protective gear to avoid possible injury. </li>\r\n<li>\r\nYou can skate at a comfortable pace for 30 minutes straight. If you want a cardio challenge, do interval skating &acirc;&#128;&#147; speed skate two minutes of every five minutes, using the remaining three minutes to recover. A 150 lb person will typically burn about 175 calories in 30 minutes skating at a comfortable pace, similar to brisk walking. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,46,47,90,1,46,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/skating',3,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/654/Male/m/654_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/654/Male/m/654_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/654/Male/m/654_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/654/Female/m/654_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/654/Female/m/654_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/654/Female/m/654_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (755,'Stairmaster','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, step onto the stairmaster and select the desired option from the menu. You can choose a manual setting, or you can select a program to run. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. </li>\r\n<li>Pump your legs up and down in an established rhythm, driving the pedals down but not all the way to the floor. It is recommended that you maintain your grip on the handles so that you don&acirc;&#128;&#153;t fall. The handles can be used to monitor your heart rate to help you stay at an appropriate intensity.</li>\r\n<li>\r\nStairmasters offer convenience, cardiovascular benefits, and usually have less impact than running outside. They are typically much harder than other cardio equipment. A 150 lb person will typically burn over 300 calories in 30 minutes, compared to about 175 calories walking. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',4,48,49,100,1,46,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/stairmaster',3,'8.2',4,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/655/Male/m/655_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/655/Male/m/655_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/655/Female/m/655_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/655/Female/m/655_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (756,'Step Mill','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>To begin, step onto the stepmill and select the desired option from the menu. You can choose a manual setting, or you can select a program to run. Typically, you can enter your age and weight to estimate the amount of calories burned during exercise. Use caution so that you don&acirc;&#128;&#153;t trip as you climb the stairs. It is recommended that you maintain your grip on the handles so that you don&acirc;&#128;&#153;t fall. </li>\r\n<li>\r\n\r\nStepmills offer convenience, cardiovascular benefits, and usually have less impact than running outside while offering a similar rate of calories burned. They are typically much harder than other cardio equipment. A 150 lb person will typically burn over 300 calories in 30 minutes, compared to about 175 calories walking. </li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,50,51,110,1,46,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/step-mill',3,'0.0',4,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/656/Male/m/656_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/656/Male/m/656_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/656/Female/m/656_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/656/Female/m/656_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/656/Female/m/656_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
 (757,'Trail Running/Walking','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Running or hiking on trails will get the blood pumping and heart beating almost immediately. Make sure you have good shoes. While you use the muscles in your calves and buttocks to pull yourself up a hill, the knees, joints and ankles absorb the bulk of the pounding coming back down. Take smaller steps as you walk downhill, keep your knees bent to reduce the impact and slow down to avoid falling.</li>\r\n<li> A 150 lb person can burn over 200 calories for 30 minutes walking uphill, compared to 175 on a flat surface. If running the trail, a 150 lb person can burn well over 500 calories in 30 minutes.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',1,52,53,120,1,46,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/trail-runningwalking',3,'9.2',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/657/Male/m/657_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/657/Male/m/657_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/657/Male/m/657_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/657/Female/m/657_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/657/Female/m/657_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/7.gif'),
