 (793,'Power Snatch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li> Begin with a loaded barbell on the floor. The bar should be close to or touching the shins, and a wide grip should be taken on the bar. The feet should be directly below the hips, with the feet turned out as needed. Lower the hips, with the chest up and the head looking forward. The shoulders should be just in front of the bar. This will be the starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Begin the first pull by driving through the front of the heels, raising the bar from the ground. The back angle should stay the same until the bar passes the knees.</li>\r\n<li> Transition into the second pull by extending through the hips knees and ankles, driving the bar up as quickly as possible. The bar should be close to the body. At peak extension, shrug the shoulders and allow the elbows to flex to the side.</li>\r\n<li> As you move your feet into the receiving position, a slightly wider position, pull yourself below the bar as you elevate the bar overhead. The bar should be received in a partial squat. Continue raising the bar to the overhead position, receiving the bar locked out overhead. </li>\r\n<li>Return to a standing position with the weight over head.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1131,1132,200,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/power-snatch',2,'9.1',2,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/703/Male/m/703_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/703/Male/m/703_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/703/Male/m/703_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/703/Male/m/703_4.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/703/Female/m/703_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/703/Female/m/703_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/703/Female/m/703_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/703/Female/m/703_4.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (794,'Reverse Band Sumo Deadlift','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Begin with a bar loaded on the floor inside of a power rack. Attach bands to the top of the rack, using either pegs or the frame itself. Attach the other end to the barbell.</li>\r\n<li> Approach the bar so that the bar intersects the middle of the feet. The feet should be set very wide, near the collars. Bend at the hips to grip the bar. The arms should be directly below the shoulders, inside the legs, and you can use a pronated grip, a mixed grip, or hook grip. Relax the shoulders, which in effect lengthens your arms. </li>\r\n<li>Take a breath, and then lower your hips, looking forward with your head with your chest up. Drive through the floor, spreading your feet apart, with your weight on the back half of your feet. Extend through the hips and knees.</li>\r\n<li> As the bar passes through the knees, lean back and drive the hips into the bar, pulling your shoulder blades together.</li>\r\n<li> Return the weight to the ground by bending at the hips and controlling the weight on the way down.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1133,1134,210,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/reverse-band-sumo-deadlift',2,'0.0',4,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/758/Male/m/758_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/758/Male/m/758_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (795,'Romanian Deadlift','\n        <p>\n        </p><p></p><ol><li> Put a barbell in front of you on the ground and grab it using a pronated (palms facing down) grip that a little wider than shoulder width. <strong>Tip:</strong> Depending on the weight used, you may need wrist wraps to perform the exercise and also a raised platform in order to allow for better range of motion.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Bend the knees slightly and keep the shins vertical, hips back and back straight. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>  Keeping your back and arms completely straight at all times, use your hips to lift the bar as you exhale. <strong>Tip:</strong> The movement should not be fast but steady and under control.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>  Once you are standing completely straight up, lower the bar by pushing the hips back, only slightly bending the knees, unlike when squatting. <strong>Tip:</strong> Take a deep breath at the start of the movement and keep your chest up. Hold your breath as you lower and exhale as you complete the movement.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.</li>\r\n</ol><p><strong>Caution:</strong> This is not an exercise that is recommended for people with lower back problems.  Also, it needs to be treated with the utmost respect paying special attention not to round the back forward too much as you move the torso.  Finally, jerking motions or doing too much weight can injure your back.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Variation:</strong> The exercise can also be performed with dumbbells in each hand.</p>\n    \n',0,1135,1136,220,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/romanian-deadlift',2,'8.8',2,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/171/Male/m/171_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/171/Male/m/171_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/171/Female/m/171_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/171/Female/m/171_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (796,'Romanian Deadlift from Deficit','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Begin standing while holding a bar at arm&acirc;&#128;&#153;s length in front of you.  You can stand on a raised platform to increase the range of motion. </li>\r\n<li>Begin by flexing the knees slightly, and then flex at the hip, moving your butt back as far as possible, lowering the torso as far as flexibility allows. The back should remain in absolute extension at all times, and the bar should remain in contact with the legs. If done properly, there should be heavy tension felt in the hamstrings.</li>\r\n<li> Reverse the motion to return to the starting position.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1137,1138,230,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/romanian-deadlift-from-deficit',2,'9.3',2,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/751/Male/m/751_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/751/Male/m/751_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/751/Female/m/751_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/751/Female/m/751_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (797,'Seated Leg Curl','\n        <p>\n        </p><p></p><ol><li>Adjust the machine lever to fit your height and sit on the machine with your back against the back support pad.</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Place the back of lower leg on top of padded lever (just a few inches under the calves) and secure the lap pad against your thighs, just above the knees. Then grasp the side handles on the machine as you point your toes straight (or you can also use any of the other two stances) and ensure that the legs are fully straight right in front of you.  This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n\r\n<li>As you exhale, pull the machine lever as far as possible to the back of your thighs by flexing at the knees. Keep your torso stationary at all times.  Hold the contracted position for a second.</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Slowly return to the starting position as you breathe in.</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.</li>\r\n</ol><p><strong>Caution:</strong> Do not ever use so much weight on the exercise that you start using swinging and jerking as you can risk both lower back injury and also a hamstring tear.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Variations:</strong> Since you have three foot positions you have in reality three exercises.</p>\r\n\n    \n',0,1139,1140,240,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/seated-leg-curl',1,'7.9',2,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/69/Male/m/69_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/69/Male/m/69_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/69/Female/m/69_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/69/Female/m/69_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (798,'Smith Machine Stiff-Legged Deadlift','\n        <p>\n        </p><p></p><ol><li> To begin, set the bar on the smith machine to a height that is around the middle of your thighs.  Once the correct height is chosen and the bar is loaded, grasp the bar using a pronated (palms forward) grip that is shoulder width apart.  You may need some wrist wraps if using a significant amount of weight.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>  Lift the bar up by fully extending your arms while keeping your back straight.  Stand with your torso straight and your legs spaced using a shoulder width or narrower stance.  The knees should be slightly bent.  This is your starting position.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>  Keeping the knees stationary, lower the barbell to over the top of your feet by bending at the waist while keeping your back straight. Keep moving forward as if you were going to pick something from the floor until you feel a stretch on the hamstrings.  Exhale as you perform this movement</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Start bringing your torso up straight again as soon as you feel the hamstrings stretch by extending your hips and waist until you are back at the starting position.  Inhale as you perform this movement.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.</li>\r\n</ol><p><strong>Caution:</strong> This is not an exercise that is recommended for people with lower back problems.  Also, it needs to be treated with the utmost respect paying special attention not to round the back forward as you move the torso down; the back should always be straight.  Finally, jerking motions or doing too much weight can injure your back.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Variations:</strong> The exercise can also be performed with dumbbells or a straight bar.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like the <a href=\"http://www.bodybuilding.com/fun/exercises.php?Name=Stiff-Legged+Barbell+Deadlift\">Stiff-Legged Deadlift</a> but with a Smith Machine.</p>\n    \n',0,1141,1142,250,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/smith-machine-stiff-legged-deadlift',2,'5.9',2,10,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/67/Male/m/67_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/67/Male/m/67_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/67/Female/m/67_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/67/Female/m/67_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (799,'Snatch Deadlift','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>The snatch deadlift strengthens the first pull of the snatch. Begin with a wide snatch grip with the barbell placed on the platform. The feet should be directly under the hips, with the feet turned out. Squat down to the bar, keeping the back in absolute extension with the head facing forward.</li>\r\n<li> Initiate the movement by driving through the heels, raising the hips. The back angle should remain the same until the bar passes the knees.</li>\r\n<li> At that point, drive your hips through the bar as you lay back. Return the bar to the platform by reversing the motion.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1143,1144,260,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/snatch-deadlift',2,'0.0',2,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/716/Male/m/716_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/716/Male/m/716_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/716/Female/m/716_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/716/Female/m/716_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (800,'Snatch Pull','\n        <p>\n         </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>With a barbell on the floor close to the shins, take a wide snatch grip. Lower your hips with the weight focused on the heels, back  straight, head facing forward, chest up, with your shoulders just in front of the bar. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Begin the first pull by driving through the heels, extending your knees. Your back angle should stay the same, and your arms should remain straight. Move the weight with control as you continue to above the knees. </li>\r\n<li>Next comes the second pull, the main source of acceleration for the pull. As the bar approaches the mid-thigh position, begin extending through the hips. In a jumping motion, accelerate by extending the hips, knees, and ankles, using speed to move the bar upward.</li>\r\n<li> There should be no need to actively pull through the arms to accelerate the weight; at the end of the second pull, the body should be fully extended, leaning slightly back. Full extension should be violent and abrupt, and ensure that you do not prolong the extension for longer than necessary.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1145,1146,270,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/snatch-pull',2,'0.0',2,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/717/Male/m/717_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/717/Male/m/717_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/717/Male/m/717_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/717/Female/m/717_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/717/Female/m/717_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/717/Female/m/717_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (801,'Split Snatch','\n        <p>\n         </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Begin with a loaded barbell on the floor. The bar should be close to or touching the shins, and a wide grip should be taken on the bar. The feet should be directly below the hips, with the feet turned out as needed. Lower the hips, with the chest up and the head looking forward. The shoulders should be just in front of the bar. This will be the starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Begin the first pull by driving through the front of the heels, raising the bar from the ground. The back angle should stay the same until the bar passes the knees.</li>\r\n<li> Transition into the second pull by extending through the hips knees and ankles, driving the bar up as quickly as possible. The bar should be close to the body. At peak extension, shrug the shoulders and allow the elbows to flex to the side.</li>\r\n<li> As you move your feet into the receiving position, forcefully pull yourself below the bar as you elevate the bar overhead. The feet should move forcefully to a split position, one foot forward one foot back. Receive the bar with your body as low as possible and the arms fully extended overhead.</li>\r\n<li> Keeping the bar aligned over the front of the heels, your head and chest up, drive through heels of the feet to move to a standing position, bringing your feet together.</li>\r\n<li> Carefully return the weight to floor.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1147,1148,280,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/split-snatch',2,'0.0',2,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/720/Male/m/720_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/720/Male/m/720_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/720/Male/m/720_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/720/Male/m/720_4.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/720/Female/m/720_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/720/Female/m/720_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/720/Female/m/720_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/720/Female/m/720_4.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (803,'Stiff-Legged Barbell Deadlift','\n        <p>\n        </p><p></p><ol><li>Grasp a bar using an overhand grip (palms facing down).  You may need some wrist wraps if using a significant amount of weight.</li>\r\n \r\n<li>Stand with your torso straight and your legs spaced using a shoulder width or narrower stance.  The knees should be slightly bent.  This is your starting position.</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Keeping the knees stationary, lower the barbell to over the top of your feet by bending at the hips while keeping your back straight. Keep moving forward as if you were going to pick something from the floor until you feel a stretch on the hamstrings.  Inhale as you perform this movement.</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Start bringing your torso up straight again by extending your hips until you are back at the starting position.  Exhale as you perform this movement.</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.</li>\r\n</ol><p><strong>Caution:</strong> This is not an exercise that is recommended for people with lower back problems.  Also, it needs to be treated with the utmost respect paying special attention not to round the back forward as you move the torso down; the back should always be straight.  Finally, jerking motions or doing too much weight can injure your back.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Variations:</strong> The exercise can also be performed with a dumbbell as described above.</p>\r\n\n    \n',0,1151,1152,300,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/stiff-legged-barbell-deadlift',2,'8.1',2,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/21/Male/m/21_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/21/Male/m/21_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/21/Female/m/21_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/21/Female/m/21_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (804,'Stiff-Legged Dumbbell Deadlift','\n        <p>\n        </p><p></p><ol><li>  Grasp a couple of dumbbells holding them by your side at arm\'s length.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>  Stand with your torso straight and your legs spaced using a shoulder width or narrower stance.  The knees should be slightly bent.  This is your starting position.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>  Keeping the knees stationary, lower the dumbbells to over the top of your feet by bending at the waist while keeping your back straight. Keep moving forward as if you were going to pick something from the floor until you feel a stretch on the hamstrings.  Exhale as you perform this movement</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Start bringing your torso up straight again by extending your hips and waist until you are back at the starting position.  Inhale as you perform this movement.</li>\r\n\r\n	<li> Repeat for the recommended amount of repetitions.</li>\r\n</ol><p><strong>Caution:</strong> This is not an exercise that is recommended for people with lower back problems.  Also, it needs to be treated with the utmost respect paying special attention not to round the back forward as you move the torso down; the back should always be straight.  Finally, jerking motions or doing too much weight can injure your back.\r\n\r\n</p><p><strong>Variations:</strong> The exercise can also be performed with a barbell also.</p>\n    \n',0,1153,1154,310,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/stiff-legged-dumbbell-deadlift',2,'9.0',2,5,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/22/Male/m/22_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/22/Male/m/22_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/22/Female/m/22_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/22/Female/m/22_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (805,'Sumo Deadlift','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Begin with a bar loaded on the ground. Approach the bar so that the bar intersects the middle of the feet. The feet should be set very wide, near the collars. Bend at the hips to grip the bar. The arms should be directly below the shoulders, inside the legs, and you can use a pronated grip, a mixed grip, or hook grip. Relax the shoulders, which in effect lengthens your arms.</li>\r\n<li> Take a breath, and then lower your hips, looking forward with your head with your chest up. Drive through the floor, spreading your feet apart, with your weight on the back half of your feet. Extend through the hips and knees.</li>\r\n<li> As the bar passes through the knees, lean back and drive the hips into the bar, pulling your shoulder blades together. </li>\r\n<li>Return the weight to the ground by bending at the hips and controlling the weight on the way down.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1155,1156,320,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/sumo-deadlift',2,'8.5',4,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/722/Male/m/722_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/722/Male/m/722_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/722/Female/m/722_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/722/Female/m/722_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (806,'Sumo Deadlift with Bands','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li> To deadlift with short bands, simply loop them over the bar before you start, and step into them to set up.  Ensure that they under the back half of your foot, directly where you are driving into the floor.</li>\r\n<li> Begin with a bar loaded on the ground. Approach the bar so that the bar intersects the middle of the feet. The feet should be set very wide, near the collars. Bend at the hips to grip the bar. The arms should be directly below the shoulders, inside the legs, and you can use a pronated grip, a mixed grip, or hook grip.</li>\r\n<li>  Take a breath, and then lower your hips, looking forward with your head with your chest up. Drive through the floor, spreading your feet apart, with your weight on the back half of your feet. Extend through the hips and knees.</li>\r\n<li> As the bar passes through the knees, lean back and drive the hips into the bar, pulling your shoulder blades together. </li>\r\n<li>Return the weight to the ground by bending at the hips and controlling the weight on the way down.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1157,1158,330,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/sumo-deadlift-with-bands',2,'0.0',2,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/723/Male/m/723_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/723/Male/m/723_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/723/Female/m/723_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/723/Female/m/723_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (807,'Sumo Deadlift with Chains','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>You can attach the chains to the sleeves of the bar, or just drape the middle over the bar so there is a greater weight increase as you lift. Attempt to keep the ends of the chains away from the plates so you don\'t hit them when you lower the weight. </li>\r\n<li>Begin with a bar loaded on the ground. Approach the bar so that the bar intersects the middle of the feet. The feet should be set very wide, near the collars. Bend at the hips to grip the bar. The arms should be directly below the shoulders, inside the legs, and you can use a pronated grip, a mixed grip, or hook grip. Relax the shoulders, which in effect lengthens your arms.</li>\r\n<li> Take a breath, and then lower your hips, looking forward with your head with your chest up. Drive through the floor, spreading your feet apart, with your weight on the back half of your feet. Extend through the hips and knees.</li>\r\n<li> As the bar passes through the knees, lean back and drive the hips into the bar, pulling your shoulder blades together.</li>\r\n<li> Return the weight to the ground by bending at the hips and controlling the weight on the way down.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1159,1160,340,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/sumo-deadlift-with-chains',2,'7.8',2,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/724/Male/m/724_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/724/Male/m/724_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/724/Female/m/724_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/724/Female/m/724_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (808,'Wide Stance Stiff Legs','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Begin with a barbell loaded on the floor. Adopt a wide stance, and then bend at the hips to grab the bar. Your hips should be as far back as possible, and your legs nearly straight. Keep your back straight, and your head and chest up. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Begin the movement be engaging the hips, driving them forward as you allow the arms to hang straight. Continue until you are standing straight up, and then slowly return the weight to the starting position. For successive reps, the weight need not touch the floor.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1161,1162,350,2,64,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/wide-stance-stiff-legs',2,'0.0',2,2,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/744/Male/m/744_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/744/Male/m/744_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/744/Female/m/744_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/744/Female/m/744_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (809,'90/90 Hamstring','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>\r\nLie on your back, with one leg extended straight out. </li>\r\n<li>With the other leg, bend the hip and knee to 90 degrees. You may brace your leg with your hands if necessary. This will be your starting position. </li>\r\n<li>\r\nExtend your leg straight into the air, pausing briefly at the top. Return the leg to the starting position. </li>\r\n<li>\r\nRepeat for 10-20 repetitions, and then switch to the other leg.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1393,1394,10,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/9090-hamstring',3,'4.3',4,3,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/578/Male/m/578_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/578/Male/m/578_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/578/Female/m/578_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/578/Female/m/578_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (810,'Chair Leg Extended Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Sit upright in a chair and grip the seat on the sides. </li>\r\n<li> Raise one leg, extending the knee, flexing the ankle as you do so.</li>\r\n<li> Slowly move that leg outward as far as you can, and then back to the center and down.</li>\r\n<li> Repeat for your other leg.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1395,1396,20,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/chair-leg-extended-stretch',1,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/486/Male/m/486_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/486/Male/m/486_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/486/Male/m/486_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/486/Female/m/486_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/486/Female/m/486_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/486/Female/m/486_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (811,'Front Leg Raises','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Stand next to a chair or other support, holding on with one hand.</li>\r\n<li> Swing your leg forward, keeping the leg straight. Continue with a downward swing, bringing the leg as far back as your flexibility allows. Repeat 5-10 times, and then switch legs.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1397,1398,30,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/front-leg-raises',3,'7.8',4,3,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/589/Male/m/589_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/589/Male/m/589_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/589/Female/m/589_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/589/Female/m/589_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (812,'Hamstring Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Lie on your back with one leg extended above you, with the hip at ninety degrees. Keep the other leg flat on the floor.</li>\r\n<li> Loop a belt, band, or rope over the ball of your foot. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Pull on the belt to create tension in the calves and hamstrings. Hold this stretch for 10-30 seconds, and repeat with the other leg.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1399,1400,40,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/hamstring-stretch',1,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/453/Male/m/453_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/453/Male/m/453_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/453/Female/m/453_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/453/Female/m/453_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (813,'Hamstring-SMR','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>In a seated position, extend your legs over a foam roll so that it is position on the back of the upper legs. Place your hands to the side or behind you to help support your weight. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Using your hands, lift your hips off of the floor and shift your weight on the foam roll to one leg. Relax the hamstrings of the leg you are stretching.</li>\r\n<li> Roll over the foam from below the hip to above the back of the knee, pausing at points of tension for 10-30 seconds. Repeat for the other leg.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1401,1402,50,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/hamstring-smr',1,'0.0',4,8,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/593/Male/m/593_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/593/Male/m/593_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/593/Female/m/593_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/593/Female/m/593_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (814,'Intermediate Groin Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Lie on your back with your legs extended. Loop a belt, rope, or band around one of your feet, and swing that leg as far to the side as you can. This will be your starting position. </li>\r\n<li>Pull gently on the belt to create tension in your groin and hamstring muscles. Hold for 10-20 seconds, and repeat on the other side.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1403,1404,60,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/intermediate-groin-stretch',1,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/595/Male/m/595_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/595/Male/m/595_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/595/Female/m/595_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/595/Female/m/595_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (815,'Leg-Up Hamstring Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Lie flat on your back, bend one knee, and put that foot flat on the floor to stabilize your spine.</li>\r\n<li> Extend the other leg in the air. If you\'re tight, you wont be able to straighten it. That\'s okay. Extend the knee so that the sole of the lifted foot faces the ceiling (or as close as you can get it).</li>\r\n<li> Slowly straighten the legs as much as possible and then pull the leg toward your nose.  Switch sides.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1405,1406,70,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/leg-up-hamstring-stretch',1,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/429/Male/m/429_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/429/Male/m/429_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/429/Female/m/429_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/429/Female/m/429_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (816,'Lying Hamstring','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Lie on your back with your legs extended. Your partner should be kneeling beside you. Raise one leg up towards the ceiling and have your partner hold the ankle. Your partner can use their shoulder to brace your leg if necessary. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> With your partner holding your leg in place, attempt to flex the knee, contracting the hamstrings for 10-20 seconds.</li>\r\n<li> Then relax your leg, allowing your partner to gently push the leg towards your head. Be sure to inform your helper when the stretch is adequate to prevent injury or overstretching. Switch sides once complete.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1407,1408,80,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/lying-hamstring',3,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/606/Male/m/606_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/606/Male/m/606_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/606/Female/m/606_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/606/Female/m/606_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (817,'Runner\'s Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>It\'s easiest to get into this stretch if you start standing up, put one leg behind you, and slowly lower your torso down to the floor.</li>\r\n<li> Keep the front heel on the floor (if it lifts up, scoot your other leg further back). </li>\r\n<li>Place your hands on either side of your front leg. To get more out of this stretch, push your butt up toward the ceiling, and then gradually lower it back toward the floor. You\'ll Stretch the hip flexor of the back leg and the hamstring and buttocks of the front.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1409,1410,90,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/runners-stretch',3,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/436/Male/m/436_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/436/Male/m/436_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/436/Female/m/436_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/436/Female/m/436_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (818,'Seated Floor Hamstring Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Sit on a mat with your right leg extended in front of you and your left leg bent with your foot against your right inner thigh.</li>\r\n<li> Lean forward from your hips and reach for your ankle until you feel a stretch in your hamstring. Hold for 15 seconds, then repeat for your other side.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1411,1412,100,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/seated-floor-hamstring-stretch',3,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/473/Male/m/473_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/473/Male/m/473_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/473/Female/m/473_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/473/Female/m/473_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (819,'Seated Hamstring','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>In a seated position with your legs extended, have your partner stand behind you. Now, lean forward as your partner braces your shoulders with their hands. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Attempt to push your torso back for 10-20 seconds, as your partner prevents any actual movement of your torso.</li>\r\n<li> Now relax your muscles as your partner increases the stretch by gently pushing your torso forward for 10-20 seconds.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1413,1414,110,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/seated-hamstring',3,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/621/Male/m/621_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/621/Male/m/621_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/621/Female/m/621_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/621/Female/m/621_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (820,'Seated Hamstring and Calf Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Loop a belt, rope, or band around one foot. Sit down with both legs extended . This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Leaning forward slightly, pull on the belt to draw the toes of your foot back. Hold this position for 10-20 seconds and then repeat with the other leg.  </li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1415,1416,120,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/seated-hamstring-and-calf-stretch',3,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/622/Male/m/622_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/622/Male/m/622_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/622/Female/m/622_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/622/Female/m/622_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (821,'Split Squats','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Being in a standing position. Jump into a split leg position, with one leg forward and one leg back, flexing the knees and lowering your hips slightly as you do so.</li>\r\n<li> As you descend, immediately reverse direction, standing back up and jumping, reversing the position of your legs. Repeat 5-10 times on each leg.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1417,1418,130,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/split-squats',3,'3.3',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/630/Male/m/630_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/630/Male/m/630_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/630/Female/m/630_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/630/Female/m/630_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/630/Female/m/630_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/630/Female/m/630_4.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (822,'Standing Hamstring and Calf Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>\r\nBeing by looping a belt, band, or rope around one foot. While standing, place that foot forward. </li>\r\n<li>Bend your back leg, while keeping the front one straight. Now raise the toes of your front foot off of the ground and lean forward.</li>\r\n<li> Using the belt, pull on the top of the foot to increase the stretch in the calf. Hold for 10-20 seconds and repeat with the other foot.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1419,1420,140,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/standing-hamstring-and-calf-stretch',3,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/638/Male/m/638_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/638/Male/m/638_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/638/Female/m/638_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/638/Female/m/638_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (823,'Standing Toe Touches','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Stand with some space in front and behind you. </li>\r\n<li>Bend at the waist, keeping your legs straight, until you can relax and let your upper body hang down in front of you. Let your arms and hands hang down naturally. Hold for 10 to 20 seconds.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1421,1422,150,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/standing-toe-touches',3,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/494/Male/m/494_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/494/Male/m/494_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/494/Female/m/494_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/494/Female/m/494_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (824,'The Straddle','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Begin in a seated, upright position. Start by extending your legs in front of you in a V.</li>\r\n<li> With your hands on the floor, lean forward as far as possible. Hold for 10 to 20 seconds.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1423,1424,160,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/the-straddle',3,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/418/Male/m/418_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/418/Male/m/418_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/418/Female/m/418_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/418/Female/m/418_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (825,'Upper Back-Leg Grab','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>While seated, bend forward to hug your thighs from underneath with both arms. </li>\r\n<li>Keep your knees together and your legs extended out as you bring your chest down to your knees. You can also stretch your middle back by pulling your back away from your knees as your hugging them.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1425,1426,170,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/upper-back-leg-grab',3,'0.0',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/457/Male/m/457_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/457/Male/m/457_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/457/Female/m/457_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/457/Female/m/457_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (826,'World\'s Greatest Stretch','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>This is a three-part stretch. Begin by lunging forward, with your front foot flat on the ground and on the toes of your back foot. With your knees bent, squat down until your knee is almost touching the ground. Keep your torso erect, and hold this position for 10-20 seconds.</li>\r\n<li> Now, place the arm on the same side as your front leg on the ground, with the elbow next to the foot. Your other hand should be placed on the ground, parallel to your lead leg, to help support you during this portion of the stretch.</li>\r\n<li> After 10-20 seconds, place your hands on either side of your front foot. Raise the toes of the front foot off of the ground, and straighten your leg. You may need to reposition your rear leg to do so. Hold for 10-20 seconds, and then repeat the entire sequence for the other side.</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1427,1428,180,2,772,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/worlds-greatest-stretch',3,'7.3',4,12,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/632/Male/m/632_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/632/Male/m/632_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/632/Male/m/632_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/632/Female/m/632_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/632/Female/m/632_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/632/Female/m/632_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/632/Female/m/632_4.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (827,'Box Jump (Multiple Response)','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Assume a relaxed stance facing the box or platform approximately an arm\'s length away. Arms should be down at the sides and legs slightly bent.</li>\r\n<li> Using the arms to aid in the initial burst, jump upward and forward, landing with feet simultaneously on top of the box or platform. </li>\r\n<li>Immediately drop or jump back down to the original starting place; then repeat the sequence.\r\n\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1589,1590,10,2,773,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/box-jump-multiple-response',2,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/766/Male/m/766_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/766/Male/m/766_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/766/Female/m/766_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/766/Female/m/766_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (828,'Hurdle Hops','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Set up a row of hurdles or other small barriers, placing them a few feet apart.</li>\r\n<li> Stand in front of the first hurdle with your feet shoulder width apart. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Begin by jumping with both feet over the first hurdle, swinging both arms as you jump. </li>\r\n<li>Absorb the impact of landing by bending the knees, rebounding out of the first leap by jumping over the next hurdle. Continue until you have jumped over all of the hurdles.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1591,1592,20,2,773,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/hurdle-hops',2,'0.0',4,13,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/788/Male/m/788_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/788/Male/m/788_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/788/Male/m/788_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/788/Female/m/788_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/788/Female/m/788_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/788/Female/m/788_3.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
 (829,'Knee Tuck Jump','\n        <p>\n        </p><p>\r\n</p><ol><li>Begin in a comfortable standing position with your knees slightly bent. Hold your hands in front of you, palms down with your fingertips together at chest height. This will be your starting position.</li>\r\n<li> Rapidly dip down into a quarter squat and immediately explode upward. Drive the knees towards the chest, attempting to touch them to the palms of the hands.</li>\r\n<li> Jump as high as you can, raising your knees up, and then ensure a good land be re-extending your legs, absorbing impact through be allowing the knees to rebend.\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\n',0,1593,1594,30,2,773,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/detail/view/name/knee-tuck-jump',2,'0.0',4,3,'http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/793/Male/m/793_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/793/Male/m/793_2.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/793/Male/m/793_3.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/793/Female/m/793_1.jpg,http://www.bodybuilding.com/exercises/exerciseImages/sequences/793/Female/m/793_2.jpg','http://assets.bodybuilding.com/images/trackers/exercise/heatmap/8.gif'),
